commits.message:
fix: resolve calendar accessibility and touch event handling issues

- Fix aria-controls accessibility by adding unique IDs per date column
- Add pointer-events-auto to event items for proper click/drag functionality
- Mark overlay container as aria-hidden for better accessibility
- Fix long-press touch event handling with proper cleanup and guards
- Remove duplicate event listeners during drag operations

Add unofficial internal cooldown to establishing game connections (#431)

As-is, the client can spam successful game server connections as there's a window between it connecting and sending the WIZ_VERSION_CHECK packet, and it getting a response. In this window, the player can initiate another request, causing it to establish another connection. If the WIZ_VERSION_CHECK packet from the first connection is received, it ends up associating the wrong encryption key -- because that's no longer the session it's using it for.

Notably this is, for the most part, official behaviour. It is very possible to continue to spam the game server with the official client, but they force a 1s delay between connection requests which limits the frequency you can actually spam. The bug is still very much an issue there though.

The official Sleep() approach isn't ideal; it doesn't really solve a lot. We should simply be unable to establish a new game server connection while we're waiting for the WIZ_VERSION_CHECK response. This is unofficial behaviour of course, but it doesn't really affect compatibility between clients (only its connection behaviour for testing). As it is, this causes (more) unintentional disconnects at login, which I'd argue makes it harder to even get to testing 99% of other behaviour, so it should still be improved.

The official Sleep() approach doesn't really prevent the inconsistency of the unintentional "failures". All it does is it stops the game server from being excessively flooded with new connections, since it throttles it to 1 a second.

Instead, we enforce a 5 second internal cooldown on ConnectToGameServer() calls. 5 seconds is plenty of time to receive a packet, even with lag. This is reset if we detect a disconnect, and the timer otherwise ticked down in GameProcLogIn_1098::Tick() / CGameProcLogIn_1298::Tick().

This is further reset when we return back to the login scene (on Init()), so returning and selecting a new server doesn't force the player to unnecessarily wait.

This prevents us from accidentally or otherwise attempting to connect multiple times, causing mixed WIZ_VERSION_CHECK request handling and thus incorrect encryption states/keys from being used.

Resolves #430

pull_request.title: fix: handle locals() calls in wrapped modules by static analysis
pull_request.body:
## Summary

This PR fixes bundling of modules that use `locals()` to dynamically access imported symbols, a pattern used by libraries like httpx to set `__module__` attributes.

## Changes

- **Static analysis for `locals()` calls**: When a module-level `locals()` call is detected, it's replaced with a statically determined dictionary containing all module-level symbols
- **`__all__` reference detection**: Added detection for when `__all__` variable is referenced elsewhere in the module (e.g., in loops), ensuring it's preserved when needed
- **AST builder enhancement**: Added `dict()` and `dict_item()` helper functions to the ast_builder for cleaner dictionary construction
- **Test fixture**: Added test case based on httpx's pattern of using `locals()` to access imported symbols

## Problem & Solution

The issue occurred when bundling modules that use this pattern:
```python
from ._internal import MyClass, my_func
__all__ = ["MyClass", "my_func"]
__locals = locals()  # Capture module-level locals
for __name in __all__:
    setattr(__locals[__name], "__module__", "mypkg")
```

In the bundled wrapper function, `locals()` returns function-local variables, not the imported symbols which are now global. The solution uses static analysis to determine what `locals()` would return at module level and replaces it with a dictionary literal containing the correct symbols.

## Test Results

- ✅ All existing tests pass
- ✅ New test fixture for the httpx pattern works correctly
- ✅ Clippy validation passes (only unused `dict_item` warning, kept for future use)

🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.ai/code)

<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->
## Summary by CodeRabbit

- New Features
  - Wrapper modules initialize once, are ordered by dependencies, and wire imports immediately during wrapper init.
  - Added a statement-level utility to detect whether a statement references a given variable and expanded per-statement progress/debug logging.

- Bug Fixes
  - locals()/globals() introspection now reliably reference the module namespace; __all__ is propagated only when referenced.
  - Import aliases and inlined exports are hoisted earlier, improving availability and export correctness.

- Refactor
  - Centralized module-namespace handling behind a single canonical module-namespace variable and unified introspection transformation.
<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->

https://github.com/unicode-org/icu4x/actions/runs/16942383109/job/48016182502

Add monotonic_year and tests (#6800)

Supersedes #6762

This also fixes the bug that we were bounds checking extended year: You
should be able to do things like `Gregorian::new(year = -100, era =
None, ...)`, but we errored here.


In the process; I discovered that Chinese was _accepting_ related_iso as
extended year, but _producing_ ICU4C extended year. This is
inconsistent.


This serves as another nail in the coffin for any ICU4C-parity guarantee
we had for extended_year, because we now have found multiple cases where
we are not handling it the ICU4C way already.

The name monotonic_year is to be bikeshed.

issue.title: Client can spam successful game server connections
issue.body:
As-is, the client can spam successful game server connections as there's a window between it connecting and sending the WIZ_VERSION_CHECK packet, and it getting a response.
In this window, the player can initiate another request, causing it to establish another connection. If the WIZ_VERSION_CHECK packet from the first connection is received, it ends up associating the wrong encryption key -- because that's no longer the session it's using it for.

Notably this is, for the most part, official behaviour.
It is very possible to continue to spam the game server with the official client, but they force a 1s delay between connection requests which limits the frequency you can actually spam.
The bug is still very much an issue there though.

The delay approach isn't ideal; it doesn't really solve a lot. We should simply be unable to establish a new game server connection while we're waiting for the WIZ_VERSION_CHECK response.
This is unofficial behaviour of course, but it doesn't really affect compatibility between clients (only its connection behaviour for testing). As it is, this causes (more) unintentional disconnects at login, which I'd argue makes it harder to even get to testing 99% of other behaviour, so it should still be improved.

The delay approach doesn't really prevent the inconsistency of the unintentional "failures". All it does is it stops the game server from being excessively flooded with new connections, since it throttles it to 1 a second.

issue.title: [Bug] Time editor subtracts 4 hours
issue.body: I was editing some dates of when I had watched shows from the history tab and discovered that upon selecting a new date and time, the timestamp saved for the episode would be off by four hours. Before hitting submit: The history tab after hitting submit showing the incorrect date: Looking at the item again, the saved timestamp is off by 4 hours: If I just keep hitting submit without manually adjusting the timestamp, the saved timestamp keeps going back 4 hours. I am in the EDT Time zone which is 4 hours off of GMT so I think this might be a bug in assuming a timestamp needs to be converted from GMT to EDT when it is already in EDT. Please let me know if you need anymore information and thanks for your incredible work!

> our auto updater that assumes it's a patch version or something ~ @Nek-12 

That sounds like a configuration issue on your end. Consult the updater's documentation on valid release patterns.

> In that case, could you please migrate to SNAPSHOTS ~ @Nek-12 

Kotest already uses [SNAPSHOTS](https://central.sonatype.com/repository/maven-snapshots/io/kotest/kotest-framework-engine/maven-metadata.xml) but they serve a different purpose (nightly / build number). The current system works fine, it's similar how Kotlin has the `Beta` and `RC` variants on central instead of a snapshot repository.

<!--  Thanks for sending a pull request!  Here are some tips for you:
1. Follow the instructions for writing a release note from k8s: https://git.k8s.io/community/contributors/guide/release-notes.md
-->

**What this PR does / why we need it**:
Updated CDIDataImportCronOutdated to fire
only if the issue is related to the
Pre-defined golden images.

Add a CDIUserDefinedDataImportCronOutdated alert
for user defined DIC that will not impact the
operator health.

Updated the namspabe label name fro ns to
namespace, since each alert should report a

pull_request.title: [BE][BOM-300] feat: 가이드 메일을 위한 점수 증가 API 구현
pull_request.body:
## 📌 What
<!-- 해결하고자 한 문제를 간결하고 명확하게 서술해주세요. -->
<!-- ex) 로그인 실패 시 에러 메시지가 출력되지 않던 문제 -->
가이드 메일을 위한 점수 증가 API를 구현했습니다.
## ❓ Why
<!-- 이 문제를 왜 해결해야 했는지, 어떤 맥락에서 발생했는지 작성해주세요. -->
<!-- ex) 사용자 피드백으로 오류 발생 시 원인 파악이 어렵다는 의견이 있었음 -->
가이드 메일을 읽어도 키우기/읽기 점수 증가를 위해서
## 🔧 How
<!-- 어떤 방식으로 해결했는지 기술적 접근 방법을 설명해주세요. -->
<!-- 주요 변경 사항, 선택한 로직이나 방법에 대한 이유가 있으면 함께 작성해주세요. -->
우선, 프론트에서 가이드메일을 관리하기로 해서, 저는 읽기 점수가 오르는 API만 구현하면 됩니다.

구현 방식에서 고민이 있었습니다.
1. 기존 아티클 읽기와 동일하게 이벤트로 구현
가이드 메일을 백엔드에서 관리하지 않기 때문에, 읽음 처리라는 것이 따로 없습니다. 그래서, 저는 점수만 올리면되는데, 이벤트로 이것을 구현하면, 불필요하게 트랜잭션이 분리되고, 가독성만 해친다고 생각했습니다.

2. GuideMailService에서 구현
- PetRepository와 3개의 ReadingRepository에 의존하여 구현
이 방식은 GuideMailService가 다른 도메인의 비즈니스 로직을 침범한다고 생각했습니다.

- PetService와 ReadingService에 의존하여 구현 (선택한 방법)
이 방식이 최선이라고 생각했습니다. 그런데, 원래 이벤트에서 사용하던 public 메서드를 활용하려 했지만, Transaction 전파를 관리하는 것에서 문제가 있었습니다. 저희는 원래 이벤트를 위해 `REQUIRED_NEW`를 사용했는데, 이렇게 하면, 키우기 점수와 읽기 점수가 따로 커밋되어 원자성을 갖지 못합니다.
그래서, 불가피하게 이벤트에서 사용되는 메서드와 비슷하거나 동일하지만 트랜잭션 전파가 다른 메서드를 만들게 되었습니다.

## 👀 Review Point (Optional)
<!-- 리뷰어에게 중점적으로 봐주었으면 하는 부분을 작성해주세요. -->
<!-- ex) 예외 처리 방식이 적절한지 확인 부탁드립니다. -->

다른 좋은 구현 방법이 있다면 알려주세요!! 
그리고, 가이드메일을 읽을 때 아티클을 읽었을 때와 **동일한 점수**를 오르게 할까요?
